              Australia's annual population growth is high in comparison with
              the majority of developed nations. Australians' reactions to
              this population growth, which migration has increasingly
              contributed to, have fluctuated significantly, with opposition to
              immigration peaking in the early 1990s before easing steadily
              around the turn of the century. Since then, the number of
              Australians opposing the level of immigration has remained
              relatively stable.

              In the last two years, however, there are signs of rising
              opposition among Australians to current levels of immigration.

              For the first time in 2018, a majority of Australians in the Lowy
              Institute annual poll expressed the view that the 'total number
              of migrants coming to Australia each year is too high'. This
              result represented a significant rise in opposition to the
              migration rate – up 14 points since 2017, and 17 points since the
              Lowy Institute first asked this question in 2014. This concern
              may reflect the current political debate about whether population
              growth causes overcrowding in Australian cities and places
              pressure on things such as public transport, roads, housing and
              other services.

              However, aside from the overall size of the intake, Australians
              have been generally positive about the benefits of immigration to
              Australia – whether economic or cultural. In 2016, most
              Australians agreed that 'overall, immigration has a positive
              impact on the economy of Australia', with 72% agreeing both that
              'accepting immigrants from many different countries makes
              Australia stronger', and that 'immigrants strengthen our country
              because of their hard work and talents'. Few agreed that
              'immigrants take away jobs from other Australians' (35%) or that
              'immigrants are a burden on our social welfare system' (40%).

